05325nam a22007095i 9780520382589DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021049403  a97805203825897 a10.1525/97805203825892doi  a(DE-B1597)613984  a(OCoLC)1334343905  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBP195.S18bR63 2022 4aBP195.S18 7aREL0370002bisacsh04a297.8/3223/eng/202202021 aRock-Singer, Aaron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn the Shade of the Sunna :bSalafi Piety in the Twentieth-Century Middle East /cAaron Rock-Singer. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tTHE ETHICS OF AN ORPHAN IMAGE -- tA NOTE ON TRANSLITERATION, SPELLING, AND DATING -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 The Roots of Salafism: Strands of an Unorthodox Past, 1926–1970 -- tChapter 2 Conquering Custom in the Name of Tawhid: The Salafi Expansion of Worship -- tChapter 3 Praying in Shoes: How To Sideline a Practice of the Prophet -- tChapter 4 The Salafi Mystique From Fitna to Gender Segregation -- tChapter 5 Leading with a Fist The Genesis and Consolidation of a Salafi Beard -- tChapter 6 Between Pants and the Jallabiyya: The Adoption of Isbal and the Battle for Authenticity -- tConclusion -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is an intellectual and social history of Salafism that moves beyond a focus on specific organizations or a commitment to the boundaries of particular nation states to trace the emergence of distinctly Salafi social practices from 1926 to the present. Salafis explicitly base their legitimacy on the word of the Qu'ran and the Sunna, and scholarship has taken them at their word by treating this movement as having sprung fully forth from Islam’s original teachings. Their distinctive public practices—praying in shoes, wearing long beards and short pants, and observing gender segregation—are thus understood to have a similarly ancient pedigree. Aaron Rock-Singer powerfully demonstrates that contemporary Salafism is in fact a creation of the twentieth century and that the movement’s signature practices emerged primarily out Salafis’ competition with other movements amidst the intellectual and social upheavals of modernity. Drawing from a range of media forms as well as traditional religious texts, Rock-Singer offers a three-dimensional portrait of a group often dismissed as a reactionary throwback to the past. In the Shade of the Sunna takes readers beyond the surface claims of Salafism’s own proponents—and the academics who often repeat them—into the larger sociocultural and intellectual forces that have definitively shaped Islam’s fastest growing revivalist movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aSalafīyahxHistoryy20th century. 0aSalafīyahxHistoryy21st century. 0aSalafīyahxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aSalafīyahxHistoryy20th century. 0aSalafīyahxHistoryy21st century. 0aSalafīyahxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2022 Englishz978311099454408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2022z9783110994537oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Califo